The day before the 20th anniversary of Britain&rsquo;s July 1, 1997 handover of Hong Kong to China, China&rsquo;s Ministry of Foreign Affairs admitted to having dispensed with its promises regarding the vibrant city. <span style="color: red;">Beijing called the Sino-British Joint Declaration (SBJD), a 1984 treaty that carefully describes the rights of Hong Kong citizens, a piece of paper that &ldquo;no longer has any practical significance.&rdquo;</span> That is an apparent violation of Article 7 of the treaty, which binds both parties to implement the SBJD in full. The city&rsquo;s Basic Law mini-constitution, which guarantees autonomy for &ldquo;at least 50 years&rdquo; with a policy of &ldquo;one country, two systems&rdquo; and a goal of universal suffrage, has also been abused by pro-Beijing interests.<br />
<br />
According to Michael C. Davis, a long time constitutional law professor at the University of Hong Kong, &ldquo;The SBJD says the Hong Kong courts are to be independent and final. The text of the Basic Law in Article 158 hardly seems to preserve that independence and the way the NPCSC [China&rsquo;s powerful Standing Committee of the National People&rsquo;s Congress] has been behaving lately comes up even shorter. <span style="color: red;">The SBJD says the legislature will be chose[n] by elections with the chief executive appointed on the basis of elections or consultations held locally.</span> Query whether the legislature has even been fully chosen by anything that would pass as elections. Of course the Basic Law promises more and that has not been done either. <span style="color: red;">That the Chinese Government is now disavowing its continued adherence to the Sino-British Joint Declaration can hardly be reassuring to Hong Kong people.</span>&rdquo;

According to a prominent foreign legal commentator teaching in China who prefers to remain anonymous, &ldquo;Chinese legal professionals also had something to say about the statement by ... the Ministry of Foreign Affairs ... The WeChat public account Empire Lawyers reprinted the Joint Declaration, asking for votes/comments on whether the Joint Declaration was legally binding ... The most upvoted comment &hellip; [said] in part[,] &quot;MFA statements have twice seriously violated the law and Constitution, this time it is whether the Joint Declaration is legally binding, with the legal quality of these people as low as this, but reflects the governing party's attitude and usual practices, it makes people shudder.&quot; It appears that even Chinese lawyers on social media find their government&rsquo;s attempts to disavow the SBJD treaty somewhat frightening.<br />
<br />
Nearly a third of the 29,000 police officers in Hong Kong were deployed to maintain order and suppress protests on July 1. Some protesters said they were attacked by pro-Beijing &ldquo;triad members&rdquo;. According to Reuters, &ldquo;A small group of pro-democracy activists near the venue were roughed up by a group of men who smashed up some props in ugly scuffles.&rdquo; Beijing used similar tactics to suppress Hong Kong&rsquo;s pro-democracy umbrella movement in 2014, but now there are calls for independence among some activists. One banner at the July 1 protest read, &ldquo;One Country, Two Systems, a cheating for twenty years. <span style="color: red;">Recapture Hong Kong with democracy and self-determination.</span>&rdquo;
